Those are false positives from the VS Code **YAML language server**, which doesn't understand CloudFormation intrinsic functions like `!Sub`, `!Ref`, `!GetAtt` by default. They're valid SAM/CloudFormation syntax — `sam validate --lint` will pass fine.

To fix the errors in the editor, install the **AWS Toolkit** extension for VS Code:

> `ms-toolsai.aws-toolkit` (or search "AWS Toolkit" in the Extensions panel)

It registers the CloudFormation/SAM JSON schema against `template.yaml` files, which teaches the YAML language server that `!Sub`, `!Ref`, `!GetAtt` etc. are valid tags. The red squiggles disappear immediately after installing.

Alternatively, if you already have the **YAML extension** (`redhat.vscode-yaml`) installed, you can manually associate the schema by adding this to your `.vscode/settings.json`:

```json
{
  "yaml.schemas": {
    "https://s3.amazonaws.com/cfn-resource-specifications-us-east-1-prod/schemas/CloudFormationV1.json": "template.yaml"
  }
}
```

The issue is likely that the file is being opened in **YAML** mode instead of **CloudFormation** mode. Check the bottom-right status bar in VS Code when [template.yaml](template.yaml) is open — it will show the current language mode.

If it says `YAML` instead of `CloudFormation`, the AWS Toolkit isn't taking ownership of the file. Fix it one of two ways:

**Option 1 — File association in settings (recommended):**
Add to your VS Code `settings.json`:
```json
{
  "files.associations": {
    "template.yaml": "cloudformation"
  }
}
```

**Option 2 — redhat YAML extension conflict:**
If you also have the `redhat.vscode-yaml` extension installed, it competes with AWS Toolkit for `.yaml` files. You can tell it to ignore `template.yaml` by adding to `settings.json`:
```json
{
  "yaml.schemas": {
    "none": "template.yaml"
  }
}
```
Or disable the YAML extension's validation for CFN files entirely:
```json
{
  "yaml.validate": false
}
```
(Though this disables validation for all YAML files — Option 1 is cleaner.)
